BAUCHI – The North-East Development Commission (NEDC) in collaboration with the Bauchi state government has commenced the training of no fewer than 150 youths on effective waste Management and recycling in order to boost economic growth and create job opportunities in Bauchi state. Speaking at the opening ceremony at the River Edge Resort In Bauchi, the Managing Director of NEDC, Mohammed Goni Alkali said that the training which will last for seven day, is aimed at equipping the participants on the modern skills in waste to wealth scheme. Represented by a consultant with the NEDC, Dr Muhammad Sanusi Ibrahim, the training will enlighten the youths on lastest trends on waste management for wealth creation via the 4Rs which is, reducing waste, reusing waste and recycling waste so that the scavengers will work under a conducive atmosphere. “The NEDC is working to ensure strict supervision to ensure that the aims and objectives are achieved by going to see how the training is impacting on the environment through practice of modern way of waste management, generation and recycling” “The commission is in partnership with the Bauchi State Government to have a workable recycling plant in the state, the issue has gone far and very soon it will be operational.The trainees will only be trained by the NEDC to improve their scavenging skills in order boost the economy as it will create more job opportunities for the teeming youths in the state” he said Speaking at the event, the Permanent Secretary, Ministry of Housing and Environments, Suleiman M. Babaji Esq said that the training which was organized by the North-East Development Commission is a clear testimony of it’s absolute commitment to the ideals of Bauchi State Government under the leadership of Sen. Bala Abdulkadir Mohammed. He also said that it is the determination of NEDC to secure a sustainable environment not only for the present generations, but also for the future ones The Permanent Secretary added that the training is specifically anchored on waste management and is not only aimed at training the youths on how to harness these waste and convert them to wealth, but to also boost their capacity by taking them through the fundamental principles of how it is done in a safe and better ways. -Advertisement- POLL “This laudable goal will no doubt contribute positively to the attainment of proper environmental sanitation and solid waste management in the State”, he said.